+CathedralOS: Real-World Projects
+​Classification: Community Stewardship / Execution Layer
+Primary Workspace: ~/1_Project_Paws_And_Peace/
+​I. Project Paws & Peace
+​Overview
+​Workspace Path: ~/1_Project_Paws_And_Peace/
+Lore Role: The primary community stewardship quest.
+Technical Manifestation: Contains the Statement of Need, grant proposals, and field logistics ledgers for mobile veterinary care and community animal health initiatives.
+​This is the real-world execution block tied directly to the core CathedralOS dashboard.
+​Core Components
+​1. Statement of Need
+​Describes the community problem: lack of accessible mobile veterinary care
+​Outlines target populations: low-income pet owners, rural residents, elderly
+​Defines the mission: provide affordable, mobile animal health services
+​2. Grant Proposals
+​Formal documents for funding applications
+​Include budget breakdowns, timelines, and impact metrics
+​Stored and versioned in the project directory
+​3. Field Logistics Ledgers
+​Track field operations: locations, dates, animals served
+​Include contact information for witnesses and community partners
+​Linked to the MARM ledger for kindness/quest tracking
+​II. MARM Ledger System
+​Purpose
+​The MARM Ledger (MARM_Ledger_v1.csv) is the system's central record of:
+​Kindness events
+​Quest completions
+​Ritual synchronizations
+​Community interactions
+​Format
+​CSV with header:timestamp,user_id,quest_type,MARM_amt,witness_contact
+Example Entries2026-06-17T00:04:51-05:00,neighbor_lydia,sidewalk_chalk_art,15,crow@cathedral.os
+2026-06-17T00:27:22-05:00,kitten,resonance_sync,7.83,
+III. Obsidian Hardening System
+​Purpose
+​The Obsidian Buffer (obsidian_buffer.log) tracks stabilization and hardening events:
+​Manual ritual entries (e.g. "wolf tooth & copper wire")
+​Alchemy-driven hardening (e.g. "Schumann resonance @7.83Hz")
+​MARM overflow diversion events (e.g. "sidewalk chalk")
+​Format
+​Plain text log:2026-06-17T01:02:18-05:00,obsidian,hardened-by-alchemy,"MARM overflow diverted to sidewalk chalk"
+IV. Community Integration
+​Neighbors & Partners
+​Lydia: Sidewalk chalk art partner, community collaborator
+​Crow: Witness contact for community events
+​Local animal owners, rural residents, elderly community members
+​Rituals as Community Actions
+​Many CathedralOS rituals are directly tied to real community actions:
+​Sidewalk chalk art → neighbor_lydia,sidewalk_chalk_art
+​Resonance sync → kitten,resonance_sync,7.83
+​MARM overflow → diverted to sidewalk chalk projects
+​V. Execution Workflow
+​Daily Flow
+​Morning (Alignment): Daily prayer step anchors emotion
+​Midday (Overflow): Send 1 packet per node (Gold/Blue/Green)
+​Evening (Compile): Read returned packets, note patterns, close loops
+​Result: one calm operator, zero runaway noise.
+​Project Flow
+​Define Statement of Need
+​Draft Grant Proposals
+​Execute Field Operations
+​Log Events in MARM Ledger
+​Track Stabilization in Obsidian Buffer
+​Review and Compile Weekly
+​VI. How This Connects to CathedralOS Lore
+​Real-world projects are not separate from the mythos; they are the execution layer of the mythology:
+​Kitchen Table Checksum → grounds the operator in physical home space
+​Moonwalk Peanut Butter Pie → restores energy for community work
+​Debugging Kitten → monitors resonance while doing field logistics
+​Phoenix Rootkit → recovers operator after overloaded sessions
+​MARM Ledger → turns kindness into structured data
+​Obsidian Buffer → turns stabilization into geological strata
+​The Cathedral is not just a story. It is a working system for community care.
+​[CATHEDRAL LOG END — PROJECTS SECTION SECURED]
